Source: Angola Press Agency (Luanda), Tue 19 Apr 2005 [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/printable/200504190577.html>

Angola: suspected cases of Marburg fever in Malanje province test negative
---------------------------------------------------
3 tons of hospital material and a car were donated on Monday [18 Apr 2005]
to the main hospital here of the northern province of Malanje by the
National Commission of Emergency and Civil Protection, created within the
scope of the program to fight Marburg virus, which has already killed 237
people. Among the materials are medicines, gloves, boots, smocks, lixivium
and a pulverizer, offered by UNICEF, and a vehicle granted by the American
oil firm Chevron Texaco. The initiative aims to prevent the sickness in the
neighboring Provinces of Northern Uije, said the coordinator of the
mentioned commission, Eugenio Laborinho; he added that the gesture will be
extensive [extended?] to Zaire, Kwanza-Norte and Bengo.
The provincial director of health in Malanje, Francisco Chagas, said that
the results of 9 test samples of suspected cases of hemorrhagic fever sent
to Luanda were negative, but technicians are still on alert for the illness.
