Date: Wed 20 Apr 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Independent online (IOL), Wed 20 Apr 2005 [edited]
<http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=14&click_id=125&art_id=qw1113981663491B256>

South Africa: quarantined air passenger has malaria not Marburg fever
---------------------------------------------------------------------
A woman who fell ill on an aircraft from Angola on Tuesday [19 Apr 2005]
night, and who was feared to have Marburg fever, appears to have malaria,
the South African health department said on Wed 20 Apr 2005.
Department spokesperson Solly Mabotha said the woman, who originally comes
from Eritrea, would be held under observation in an isolation ward at the
Johannesburg Hospital for a "while longer". "Although we have done a
thorough screening of the patient, we want to play it safe, and that's why
we're holding her for a while longer," he said. Mabotha said the
Johannesburg Hospital is one of the facilities that have been chosen to
keep suspected Marburg victims in isolation.
The woman became ill on the flight from Luanda on Tuesday [19 Apr 2005]
night shortly before it was due to land, South African Airways spokesperson
Onkgopotse JJ Tabane said. She was handed over to the airport health
authorities, because it was feared she might be infected with Marburg
virus. As a precautionary measure, the aircraft was also placed under
quarantine. "The plane has been disinfected, and we will not be using it
until we get the go-ahead," Tabane said.
